### CSS Width & Height

Set dimensions of elements.

---

### Basic Properties

```css
.box {
  width: 300px;
  height: 200px;
}
```

---

### Values

| Value | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| `auto` | Browser calculates (default) |
| `px` | Fixed pixels |
| `%` | Percentage of parent |
| `em` / `rem` | Relative to font |
| `vw` / `vh` | Relative to viewport |
| `min-content` | Width of smallest content |
| `max-content` | Width of largest content |
| `fit-content` | Shrinks to content, max at parent |

---

### Min & Max Limits

```css
.box {
  min-width: 200px;
  max-width: 800px;
  min-height: 100px;
  max-height: 500px;
}
```

Element **stays within these bounds** even if content changes.

---

### Common Patterns

```css
/* Full-width container */
.container {
  width: 100%;
  max-width: 1200px;
  margin: 0 auto;
}

/* Full viewport hero */
.hero {
  width: 100vw;
  height: 100vh;
}

/* Responsive image */
img {
  max-width: 100%;
  height: auto;
}

/* Square using aspect-ratio */
.square {
  width: 200px;
  aspect-ratio: 1 / 1;
}
```

---

### height: 100% Problem

For `height: 100%` to work, the **parent** must have a defined height:

```css
html, body {
  height: 100%;
}

.full-height {
  height: 100%; /* Works because parent has height */
}
```

---

> **Best Practice:** Use `max-width` instead of `width` for responsive elements. Use `min-height` instead of `height` for content that might grow.
